<div id="review_239036673" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/239036673" />
    <a title="Lauren" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3995558-lauren"><img alt="Lauren" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1325290409p2/3995558.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/239036673?book_show_action=true">Nov 23, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lauren" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lauren" href="/user/show/3995558-lauren">Lauren</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3995558-lauren?shelf=college">college</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3995558-lauren?shelf=realistic-fiction">realistic-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer239036673" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11115356299221133491">This book is long, incomprehensible, and downright annoying for me. Yet, it won the Nobel prize for literature in 2000. So in other words, if you read it for your own intellectual advancement, it’s fantastic. If not, well, you may just want to find another book. <p> Essentially, what makes the book frustrating is that it is not consistent or logical in any imaginable way. It doesn’t have any main characters. Instead, Gao Xingjian refers to his main characters simply as I, You, He, and She. When the</p></span>
  <span id="freeText11115356299221133491" style="display:none">This book is long, incomprehensible, and downright annoying for me. Yet, it won the Nobel prize for literature in 2000. So in other words, if you read it for your own intellectual advancement, it’s fantastic. If not, well, you may just want to find another book. <p> Essentially, what makes the book frustrating is that it is not consistent or logical in any imaginable way. It doesn’t have any main characters. Instead, Gao Xingjian refers to his main characters simply as I, You, He, and She. When these characters are involved in a conversation, it is seldom clear who is talking. Even the speakers themselves are unreliable. In almost every chapter, the topic, environment, and speaker switch off. When the readers begin a chapter with a speaker they have met, the speaker is not where they were before mentally or physically. There is no consistency in the book… unless you count this inconsistency as consistency. My professor literally told us: “it doesn’t matter where you start reading it, you could read from the beginning to the end or from the end to the beginning, either way you still have the same experience.” </p> <p>However, there must be a reason why this book was written like this and why the Nobel people love it so much. In a supremely condensed and unworthy explanation: it’s because Gao Xingjian wants to show Chinese modernity’s limitations on society and to oppose rationalism. And yes, the only reason I somehow came up with that is because I just wrote an essay on it. :) <br /></p></span>
  <a data-text-id="11115356299221133491" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


