    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2333092634" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2333092634" />
    <a title="Czarny Pies" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies"><img alt="Czarny Pies" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1400687408p2/29160274.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2333092634?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Czarny Pies" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Czarny Pies" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies">Czarny Pies</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9782757804506" href="/book/show/2735103-la-montagne-de-l-me">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Readers with a good knowledge of Chinese history especially the Cultural Revolution.</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29160274-czarny-pies?shelf=asian-literature">asian-literature</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29160274-czarny-pies?shelf=nobel-prize-winners">nobel-prize-winners</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2333092634" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12867208506479907356">&quot;Soul Mountain&apos; is a wretched work by a equally wretched man profoundly traumatized by his experiences in Communist China during an ear when an estimated 30 to 45 million Chinese would die because of the oppression and sheer incompetence of the regime. <br/>Completed in Paris in 1989 several months after the Tiananmen Square massacre &quot;Soul Mountain&quot; is an important testimony to life under Mao.<br/><br/>The protagonist narrator is a minor writer has been misdiagnosed with Lung Cancer. Two weeks later a second t</span>
  <span id="freeText12867208506479907356" style="display:none">"Soul Mountain' is a wretched work by a equally wretched man profoundly traumatized by his experiences in Communist China during an ear when an estimated 30 to 45 million Chinese would die because of the oppression and sheer incompetence of the regime. <br />Completed in Paris in 1989 several months after the Tiananmen Square massacre "Soul Mountain" is an important testimony to life under Mao.<br /><br />The protagonist narrator is a minor writer has been misdiagnosed with Lung Cancer. Two weeks later a second test reveals the first was false. The incident provokes a crisis. The protagonist becomes profoundly confused about his own identity referring to himself at different times as 'I' and 'you'. He sets out to find Lingshan , the soul mountain of the Buddha travelling with a copy of I Ching. Ultimately, he will fail in his spiritual quest because, as it is explained at the end of the novel he never asks for the "way" to the soul mountain but rather "where" it is. <br />In the course of the novel, the protagonist will visit many temples and monasteries. engaging s in long conversations with Buddhists and Taoists but will never embrace either of China's religions He shows utterly no interest in Christianity, either for or against, presumably because it is not a Chinese type of spirituality.<br />Simultaneously, the protagonist looks for the soul mountain in the traditions and folklore of the people. He visits festivals, inspects folk, l costumes, attends performances of traditional dances, and listens to music played on archaic Chinese instruments. He will collect a large number of folktales and descriptions of superstitions told to him in regional dialects. Ultimately, he concludes that there is a national soul for the Chinese people.<br />The protagonist's third activity during his journey is to reflects on Chinese history. He describes incidents from most of the Chinese dynasties (Ching, Ming, Song, Zhu, Han, etc.) of the last 2500 years but he concentrates primarily on the eras of the Warring States, the Three Kingdoms and most of all from Mao's cultural revolution. He concludes China's history is one of uninterrupted violence and atrocities against its people. He makes no mention of the crimes of the imperial powers that have invaded China. Thus he does not mention of the Opium Wars with the French and English or the Japanese invasion on Manchuria. The protagonist/narrator maintains a rigorous focus on the crimes of Chinese against Chinese.<br />Finally, the protagonist goes through a string of sexual encounters. The initial problem in this sphere is that the protagonist wants only sex. He confesses that he has always had bad relations with women because he simply projects his own fantasies on them and ignores them for what they truly are. The second problem for the protagonist is the that the women he meets want to share with him the horrors that they lived through during the communist era. The finally meeting is particularly disastrous. The protagonist meets a lesbian who lures him into her house with the offer of seafood so that she can tell him the story of how she brought about the death of the woman she loved. The story teller recounts how she had lured d a very beautiful young actress into a relationship. When the young actress later obtained the lead part in theatre production, a jealous rival would denounce her to the communists for her "counterrevolutionary" activity (i.e. lesbianism) causing the young actress to be thrown prison where she would die. Enraged that the woman telling the story had no interest in sleeping with him, the protagonist would be disgusted by the story and leave in a rage.<br />As the book ends, the protagonist narrator is wandering through a ghostly landscape wondering if we would all be better off dead. ''Soul Mountain" was written during an era in history when there was little reason to be optimistic about the future of China. It is a depressing and confusing work with little to recommend it. Its pessimistic mood is similar to that which I have encountered in novels by Daie Sijie and Shan Sa both of whom express themselves with much greater clarity. I advise readers interested in modern China to begin with these two authors.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12867208506479907356" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


