    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_24527057" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/24527057" />
    <a title="Lisa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/568109-lisa"><img alt="Lisa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1598986623p2/568109.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/24527057?book_show_action=true">Jun 14, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lisa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lisa" href="/user/show/568109-lisa">Lisa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">anyone wanting a new way of looking at fiction</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Lisa by: </span>
      someone on cafe mom, I forgot who
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer24527057" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5185379692981940495">This book can only be described as wonderfully unusual, outside the realm of the traditional work of fiction. I imagine that the book could almost be considered a memoir because the narrator has a lot of the author&apos;s same experiences.(as provided in a short introduction)My first reaction was that this book was very artistic in it&apos;s writing. The narrator seems to paint the setting in the readers mind with his descriptions while setting the mood with words so immersed in his own mood that I couldn</span>
  <span id="freeText5185379692981940495" style="display:none">This book can only be described as wonderfully unusual, outside the realm of the traditional work of fiction. I imagine that the book could almost be considered a memoir because the narrator has a lot of the author's same experiences.(as provided in a short introduction)My first reaction was that this book was very artistic in it's writing. The narrator seems to paint the setting in the readers mind with his descriptions while setting the mood with words so immersed in his own mood that I couldn't help but share in it. Throughout the book the narrator is in search of something both in his environment, and within himself. A feeling of lonliness is the narrator's constant companion and in the process transfers this lonliness to the reader. At times I found myself stopping or reading sections again because of his explaination of why the world is the way it is, and why he chose to explain the story the way he does. The often commented way Xingjian uses various pronouns when refering to himsef for example is explained by his saying<br /> "...the individual did not exist. There was not an awareness of a distinction between "I" and "you".The birth of I derived from the fear of death..." He explains also that he is talking to himself to deal with the lonliness that he has. <br />As much as I liked this book it did start to loose some of its steam for me midway through so it took a while to finish. Combine that with 2 out of 3 of my children being sick during that time made this a long and sometimes tortured read for me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5185379692981940495" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


